Definition 4.5. Assume that $W$ is an open subset of ${\rm{ASpec}}\mathcal{A}$ and $\Gamma_{W}$ preserves injective objects. For any object $M$ of $\mathcal{A}$ and $i\geq 0$, we define $i$-th local cohomology object of $M$ with respect to $W$, denoted by $H_{W}^{i}(M)$, that is $H_{W}^{i}(M)=H^{i}(\Gamma_{W}(I))$ where $I$ is an injective resolution of $M$. When $\Gamma_{W}(M)=M$, since $\Gamma_{W}$ preserves injective objects, $M$ has an injective resolution with each components $\Gamma_{W}$-torsion. This implies that $H_{W}^{i}(M)=0$ for all $i>0$. In the case $W=\{\mathfrak{m}\}$ where $\mathfrak{m}$ is a maximal atom, we denote the $i$-th local cohomology object $M$ with respect to $W$ by $H_{\mathfrak{m}}^{i}(M)$. A Grothendieck category is said to be local if ${\rm{ASpec}}\mathcal{A}$ contains only one maximal atom $\mathfrak{m}$. In this case the local category $\mathcal{A}$ is denoted by $(\mathcal{A},\mathfrak{m})$. We notice that if $\mathcal{A}$ is a local Grothendieck category in sense of [K2, Definition 6.3] or [P, Section 4.20], it is local by our definition. To be more precise, in this case, there exists a simple object $S$ such that $E(S)$ is an injective cogenerator of $\mathcal{A}$. Then for any other simple object $H$ of $\mathcal{A}$, $H$ is isomorphic to a subobject of $E(S)$ so that we deduce $H\cong S$. Therefore $\overline{S}$ is the only maximal atom of $\mathcal{A}$. Conversely, when $\mathcal{A}$ is a local locally noetherian Grothendieck category, $\mathcal{A}$ is local in sense of [K2, P]. Because if $(\mathcal{A},\mathfrak{m})$ is a local locally noetherian Grothendieck category, then any object $M$ of $\mathcal{A}$ contains a noetherian subobject $N$. Since $N$ is noetherian, it has a simple quotient object $N/N_{1}$ and since $(\mathcal{A},\mathfrak{m})$ is local, we have $\mathfrak{m}=\overline{N/N_{1}}$ so that $\mathfrak{m}\in{\rm ASupp}(M)$. It now follows from [K2, Proposition 6.4] that $\mathcal{A}$ is local in sense of [K2, P].
Definition 3.10. Let $M$ be an object of $\mathcal{A}$ and $U$ be an open subset of ${\rm{ASpec}}\mathcal{A}$. The torsion subobject of $M$ with respect to $U$ , denoted by $\theta_{M}:\Gamma_{U}(M)\rightarrow M$, is the largest subobject of $M$ such that ${\rm ASupp}(\Gamma_{U}(M))\subset U$. We notice that $\Gamma_{U}$ is called a section functor on $\mathcal{A}$ with respect to $U$. According to the definition, it is clear that $\Gamma_{U}$ is an idempotent functor (i.e. $\Gamma_{U}^{2}=\Gamma_{U}$).
Definition 5.3. Let $\mathcal{T}=\mathcal{D}^{+}(\mathcal{A})$ be the derived category of all left bounded complexes of objects of $\mathcal{A}$ and let $\delta:\mathcal{T}\rightarrow\mathcal{T}$ be a triangle functor. $\delta$ is said to be an abstract local cohomology functor if the following conditions are satisfied. (1) The natural embedding functor $i:{\rm{Im}}(\delta)\rightarrow\mathcal{T}$ has a right adjoint $\rho:\mathcal{T}\rightarrow{\rm{Im}}(\delta)$ and $\delta\cong i\circ\rho$ (Hence, by Miyachi’s Theorem, $({\rm{Im}}(\delta),{\rm{Ker}}(\delta))$ is a stable t-structure on $\mathcal{T}$.) (2) The t-structure $({\rm{Im}}(\delta),{\rm{Ker}}(\delta))$ divides indecomposable injective objects, by which we mean that each indecomposable injective object in $\mathcal{A}$ belongs to either ${\rm{Im}}(\delta)$ or ${\rm{Ker}}(\delta)$.
Definition 2.2. A full subcategory $\mathcal{X}$ of an abelian category $\mathcal{A}$ is called Serre if for any exact sequence $0\rightarrow M\rightarrow N\rightarrow K\rightarrow 0$ of $\mathcal{A}$, the object $N$ belongs to $\mathcal{X}$ if and only if $M$ and $K$ belong to $\mathcal{X}$. The quotient category $\mathcal{A}/\mathcal{X}$ of $\mathcal{A}$ induced by $\mathcal{X}$ is defined as follows. (1) The objects of $\mathcal{A}/\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{A}$ are the same. (2) For any objects $M$ and $N$ in $\mathcal{A}$ we have ${\rm{Hom}}_{\mathcal{A}/\mathcal{X}}(M,N)=\underset{\underset{(M^{\prime},N^{% \prime})\in\mathcal{S}(M,N)}{\longrightarrow}}{\mbox{lim}}{\rm{Hom}}_{\mathcal% {A}}(M^{\prime},N/N^{\prime})$ where $\mathcal{S}(M,N)$ is the direct set defined by $\mathcal{S}(M,N)=\{(M^{\prime},N^{\prime})|\hskip 2.845276ptM^{\prime}\subset M% ,N^{\prime}\subset N\hskip 2.845276pt{\rm such\hskip 2.845276ptthat}\hskip 2.8% 45276ptM/M^{\prime},N^{\prime}\in\mathcal{X}\}$ and for $(M^{\prime},N^{\prime}),(M^{\prime\prime},N^{\prime\prime})\in\mathcal{S}(M,N)$, we have $(M^{\prime},N^{\prime})\leq(M^{\prime\prime},N^{\prime\prime})$ if $M^{\prime\prime}\subset M^{\prime}$ and $N^{\prime}\subset N^{\prime\prime}$. (3) Let $L,M,N$ be objects in $\mathcal{A}$ and $[f]\in{\rm{Hom}}_{\mathcal{A}/\mathcal{X}}(L,M)$ and $[g]\in{\rm{Hom}}_{A/\mathcal{X}}(M,N)$. Assume that $[f]$ and $[g]$ are represented by $f\in{\rm{Hom}}_{\mathcal{A}}(L^{\prime},M/M^{\prime})$ and $g\in{\rm{Hom}}_{\mathcal{A}}(M^{\prime\prime},N/N^{\prime\prime})$ where $(L^{\prime},M^{\prime})\in\mathcal{S}(L,M)$ and $(M^{\prime\prime},N^{\prime\prime})\in\mathcal{S}(M,N)$, respectively. Then the composite $[g]\circ[f]\in{\rm{Hom}}_{\mathcal{S}}(L,N)$ is the equivalence class of the composite of $f^{\prime\prime}:f^{-1}(\frac{M^{\prime}+M^{\prime\prime}}{M^{\prime}})% \rightarrow\frac{M^{\prime}+M^{\prime\prime}}{M^{\prime}}$ and $g^{\prime}:\frac{M^{\prime}+M^{\prime\prime}}{M^{\prime}}\rightarrow N/N^{\prime}$ where $f^{\prime\prime}$ and $g^{\prime}$ are the induced morphisms by $f$ and $g$, respectively and $N^{\prime}/N^{\prime\prime}=g(M^{\prime}\cap M^{\prime\prime})$. In this case, we can define the canonical additive functor $F:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{A}/\mathcal{X}$ by the assignment $M\mapsto M$ for each object $M$ of $\mathcal{A}$ and the canonical map ${\rm{Hom}}_{\mathcal{A}}(M,N)\rightarrow{\rm{Hom}}_{\mathcal{A}/\mathcal{X}}(M% ,N)$ for objects $M$ and $N$ in $\mathcal{A}$. The Serre subcategory $\mathcal{X}$ of $\mathcal{A}$ is called localizing if the canonical functor $F$ has a right adjoint functor.
Definition 4.1. Given an object $M$ of $\mathcal{A}$, we define the dimension of $M$, denoted by $\dim M$, that is the largest non-negative integer $n$ such that $\alpha_{0}<\alpha_{1}<\dots<\alpha_{n}$ is a chain of atoms in ${\rm ASupp}(M)$.
Definition 2.5 (Differential of $A_{\infty}$-prenatural transformation). Let $k$ be a commutative ring with unit and $F$, $G:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be two dg $k$-functors between dg $k$-categories. Let $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ be an $A_{\infty}$ $k$-prenatural transformation of degree $n$ as in Definition 2.4. Then the differential $d\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ is an $A_{\infty}$ $k$-prenatural transformation of degree $n+1$ whose components are given as follows: 1. For any object $X\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$,$(d^{\infty}\Phi)^{0}_{X}=d(\Phi^{0}_{X})\in\mathcal{D}^{n+1}(FX,GX)$; 2. For any $l\geq 1$ and a collection of morphisms $u_{i}\in\mathcal{C}(X_{i-1},X_{i})$ $i=1,\ldots,l$, $\begin{split}&\displaystyle(d^{\infty}\Phi)^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1% })=\\ &\displaystyle d(\Phi^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1}))+(-1)^{|u_{l}|-1}G(% u_{l})\Phi^{l-1}(u_{l-1}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+(-1)^{n|u_{1}|-|u_{1}|-\ldots-|u_{l}|+l-1}\Phi^{l-1}(u_{l}% \otimes\ldots\otimes u_{2})F(u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\Phi^{l}(u_{% l}\otimes\ldots du_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l-1}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\Phi^{l-1}% (u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{i+1}u_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\end{split}$
Definition 4.1. Let $k$ be a field and $X$, $Y$ be $k$-ringed spaces. Let $F$, $G:\underline{\mathbb{I}}(X)\to\underline{\mathbb{I}}(Y)$ be two dg $k$-functors and $\Phi:F\to G$ be a dg $k$-natural transformation which is an objectwise homotopy equivalence. For each object $\mathcal{E}\in\text{obj}(\underline{\mathbb{I}}(X))$ we can choose $\Psi_{\mathcal{E}}\in\underline{\mathbb{I}}^{0}(Y)(G\mathcal{E},F\mathcal{E})$, $h_{\mathcal{E}}\in\underline{\mathbb{I}}^{-1}(Y)(F\mathcal{E},F\mathcal{E})$, $p_{\mathcal{E}}\in\underline{\mathbb{I}}^{-1}(Y)(G\mathcal{E},G\mathcal{E})$, such that $\Psi_{\mathcal{E}}\Phi_{\mathcal{E}}-\text{id}_{F\mathcal{E}}=dh_{\mathcal{E}}% ,\leavevmode\nobreak\ \Phi_{\mathcal{E}}\Psi_{\mathcal{E}}-\text{id}_{G% \mathcal{E}}=dp_{\mathcal{E}}.$ We call such a choice an objectwise homotopy inverse system of $\Phi$.
Definition 3.1. [[Sch18, 2.3.4]] Let $k$ be a field. For a morphism of $k$-ringed spaces $f:X\to Y$, we define the injective pull back dg $k$-functor $\underline{f}^{*}$ as $\underline{f}^{*}:=\mathbf{i}\circ f^{*}\circ\mathbf{e}$ Similarly we define the injective push forward dg $k$-functor $\underline{f}_{*}$ as $\underline{f}_{*}:=\mathbf{i}\circ f_{*}$ where $\mathbf{i}$ and $\mathbf{e}$ are defined in Proposition 3.1.
Definition 2.7 (Compositions). Let $k$ be a commutative ring with unit and $F$, $G$, $H:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be three dg $k$-functors between dg $k$-categories. Let $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ be a dg $k$-natural transformation and $\Psi:G\Rightarrow H$ be an $A_{\infty}$ $k$-natural transformation. Then the composition $\Psi\circ\Phi$ is defined as follows: For any object $X\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$ $(\Psi\circ\Phi)^{0}_{X}:=\Psi^{0}_{X}\Phi_{X}:FX\to GX\to HX$ and for any $u_{i}\in\mathcal{C}(X_{i-1},X_{i})$, $i=1,\ldots,l$ $(\Psi\circ\Phi)^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{1}):=\Psi^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{% 1})\Phi_{X_{0}}$ We can check that $\Psi\circ\Phi$ is an $A_{\infty}$ $k$-natural transformation. Similarly, Let $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ be an $A_{\infty}$ $k$-natural transformation and $\Psi:G\Rightarrow H$ be a dg $k$-natural transformation. Then the composition $\Psi\circ\Phi$ is defined as follows: For any object $X\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$ $(\Psi\circ\Phi)^{0}_{X}:=\Psi_{X}\Phi^{0}_{X}:FX\to GX\to HX$ and for any $u_{i}\in\mathcal{C}(X_{i-1},X_{i})$, $i=1,\ldots,l$ $(\Psi\circ\Phi)^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{1}):=\Psi_{X_{l}}\Phi^{l}(u_{l}% \otimes\ldots u_{1})$ We can check that $\Psi\circ\Phi$ is an $A_{\infty}$ $k$-natural transformation.
Definition 2.3 (dg-natural transformation). Let $k$ be a commutative ring with unit and $F$, $G:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be two dg $k$-functors between dg $k$-categories. A dg $k$-prenatural transformation $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ of degree $n$ consists of a morphism $\Phi_{X}\in\mathcal{D}^{n}(FX,GX)\text{ for each object }X$ such that for any morphism $u\in\mathcal{C}^{m}(X,Y)$ we have $\Phi_{Y}Fu=(-1)^{mn}Gu\Phi_{X}.$ The differential on $\Phi$ is defined objectwisely and it is clear that $d\Phi$ is a dg $k$-prenatural transformation of degree $n+1$. We call $\Phi$ a dg $k$-natural transformation if $\Phi$ is closed and of degree $0$.
Definition 2.1 (dg-categories). Let $k$ be a commutative ring with unit. A differential graded or dg $k$-category is a category $\mathcal{C}$ whose morphism spaces are cochain complexes of $k$-modules and whose compositions of morphisms $\mathcal{C}(Y,Z)\otimes_{k}\mathcal{C}(X,Y)\to\mathcal{C}(X,Z)$ are morphisms of $k$-cochain complexes. Furthermore, there are obvious associativity and unit axioms.
Definition 2.6 ($A_{\infty}$-natural transformation). Let $k$ be a commutative ring with unit and $F$, $G:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be two dg $k$-functors between dg $k$-categories. Let $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ be an $A_{\infty}$ $k$-prenatural transformation. We call $\Phi$ an $A_{\infty}$ $k$-natural transformation if $\Phi$ is of degree $0$ and closed under the differential $d^{\infty}$ in Definition 2.5.
Definition 2.2 (dg-functors). Let $k$ be a commutative ring with unit and $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be two dg $k$-categories. A dg $k$-functor $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ consists of the following data: 1. A map $F:\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})\to\text{obj}(\mathcal{D})$; 2. For any objects $X$, $Y\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$, a closed, degree $0$ morphism of complexes of $k$-modules $F(X,Y):\mathcal{C}(X,Y)\to\mathcal{D}(FX,FY)$ which is compatible with the composition and the units.
Definition 2.8 ($A_{\infty}$ quasi-inverse). Let $k$ be a commutative ring with unit and $F$, $G:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be two dg $k$-functors between dg $k$-categories. Let $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ be a dg $k$-natural transformation. We call an $A_{\infty}$ $k$-natural transformation $\Psi:G\Rightarrow F$ an $A_{\infty}$ quasi-inverse of $\Phi$ if there exists $A_{\infty}$ $k$-prenatural transformations $\eta:F\Rightarrow F$ and $\omega:G\Rightarrow G$ both of degree $-1$ such that $\Psi\circ\Phi-\text{id}_{F}=d^{\infty}\eta,\text{ and }\Phi\circ\Psi-\text{id}% _{G}=d^{\infty}\omega.$ In more details, this means that we have $\Psi^{0}_{X}\Phi_{X}-\text{id}_{FX}=d\eta^{0}_{X},\text{ and }\Phi_{X}\Psi^{0}% _{X}-\text{id}_{GX}=d\omega^{0}_{X}\text{ for any }X\in\text{obj}{\mathcal{C}}$ and for any $l\geq 1$ and any $u_{i}\in\mathcal{C}(X_{i-1},X_{i})$, $i=1,\ldots,l$, we have $\begin{split}&\displaystyle\Psi^{l}(\Phi(u_{l})\otimes\ldots\otimes\Phi(u_{1})% )=\\ &\displaystyle d(\eta^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1}))+(-1)^{|u_{l}|-1}G(% u_{l})\eta^{l-1}(u_{l-1}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+(-1)^{-|u_{2}|-\ldots-|u_{l}|+l-1}\eta^{l-1}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots% \otimes u_{2})F(u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\eta^{l}(u_{% l}\otimes\ldots du_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l-1}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\eta^{l-1}% (u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{i+1}u_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\end{split}$ and $\begin{split}&\displaystyle\Phi(\Psi^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1}))=\\ &\displaystyle d(\omega^{l}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1}))+(-1)^{|u_{l}|-1}% G(u_{l})\omega^{l-1}(u_{l-1}\otimes\ldots\otimes u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+(-1)^{-|u_{2}|-\ldots-|u_{l}|+l-1}\omega^{l-1}(u_{l}\otimes% \ldots\otimes u_{2})F(u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\omega^{l}(u% _{l}\otimes\ldots du_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\\ &\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{l-1}(-1)^{|u_{l}|+\ldots+|u_{i+1}|+l-i+1}\omega^{l-% 1}(u_{l}\otimes\ldots u_{i+1}u_{i}\otimes\ldots u_{1})\end{split}$
Definition 2.4 ($A_{\infty}$-prenatural transformation). Let $k$ be a commutative ring with unit and $F$, $G:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be two dg $k$-functors between dg $k$-categories. An $A_{\infty}$ $k$-prenatural transformation $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ of degree $n$ consists of the following data: 1. For any object $X\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$, a morphism $\Phi^{0}_{X}\in\mathcal{D}^{n}(FX,GX)$; 2. For any $l\geq 1$ and any objects $X_{0},\ldots,X_{l}\in\text{obj}(\mathcal{C})$, a morphism $\Phi^{l}_{X_{0},\ldots,X_{l}}\in\text{Hom}^{n-l}_{k}(\mathcal{C}(X_{l-1},X_{l}% )\otimes_{k}\ldots\otimes_{k}\mathcal{C}(X_{0},X_{1}),\mathcal{D}(FX_{0},GX_{l% }))$
Definition 3.2. [[Sch18, 2.1.3]] Let $k$ be a field and $X$, $Y$ be $k$-ringed spaces. Let $F,G:\underline{\mathbb{I}}(X)\to\underline{\mathbb{I}}(Y)$ be dg $k$-functors. A dg $k$-natural transformation $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ is called an objectwise homotopy equivalence if for any object $\mathcal{E}\in\text{obj}(\underline{\mathbb{I}}(X))$, the morphism $\Phi_{\mathcal{E}}:F\mathcal{E}\to G\mathcal{E}$ has a homotopic inverse.
Definition 3.5. An algebra $(A,\mu,\iota)$ is called separable if $\mu:A\otimes A\to A$ splits as a morphism of $A$-$A$-bimodule. Namely, there is an $A$-$A$-bimodule map $e:A\to A\otimes A$ such that $\mu\circ e=\mathrm{id}_{A}$. A separable algebra is called connected if $\dim\hom_{\mathcal{C}}(\mathbf{1},A)=1$. We will call a connected commutative separable algebra as a condensable algebra. A condensable algebra $A$ is called Lagrangian if $\dim(A)^{2}=\dim(\mathcal{C})$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a UMTC. An algebra $A$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is a triple $(A,\mu,\iota)$, where $A$ is an object in $\mathcal{C}$, $\mu:A\otimes A\to A$ and $\iota:\mathbf{1}\to A$ are morphisms satisfying the following conditions: $\mu\circ(\mu\otimes\mathrm{id}_{A})\circ\alpha_{A,A,A}=\mu\circ(\mathrm{id}_{A% }\otimes\mu).$ $\mu\circ(\iota\otimes\mathrm{id}_{A})=\mathrm{id}_{A}=\mu\circ(\mathrm{id}_{A}% \otimes\iota).$ The algebra $A$ is called commutative if $\mu=\mu\circ c_{A,A}$.
Definition 3.4. A right $A$-module in $\mathcal{C}$ is a pair $(M,\mu_{M})$, where $M$ is an object in $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mu_{M}:M\otimes A\to M$ is such that $\mu_{M}\circ(\mathrm{id}_{M}\otimes\mu)=\mu_{M}\circ(\mu_{M}\otimes\mathrm{id}% _{A})\circ\alpha_{M,A,A},\quad\quad\mu_{M}\circ(\mathrm{id}_{M}\otimes\iota)=% \mathrm{id}_{M}.$ A left module and a bimodule can be defined similarly.
2.3 Definition. A category $\mathcal{K}$ is said to have width $w(\mathcal{K})$ if it has coproducts, every object is a coproduct of connected objects, and $w(\mathcal{K})$ is the smallest cardinal such that (a) $\mathcal{K}$ has at most $w(\mathcal{K})$ connected objects up to isomorphism, and (b) there exist at most $\alpha$ morphisms from a connected object to an object of power $\alpha$, for all cardinals $\alpha\geq w(\mathcal{K})$.
2.1 Definition. An object is called connected if it is non-initial and is not a coproduct of two non-initial objects. An object is said to have power $\lambda$ if it is a coproduct of $\lambda$ connected objects.
18 Definition. We say that a type $D:\mathcal{W}$ is algebraically $\mathcal{U}$-flabby to mean ${\color[rgb]{0,0,0.4}\Pi(P:\mathcal{U}),\text{if {\color[rgb]{0,0,0.4}$P$} is % a subsingleton then {\color[rgb]{0,0,0.4}$\Pi(f:P\to D)\,\Sigma(d:D)\,\Pi(p:P)% ,d=f\,p$}.}}$
22 Definition. By a subuniverse of $\mathcal{U}$ we mean a projection $\Sigma\,A\to\mathcal{U}$ with $A:\mathcal{U}\to\mathcal{T}$ subsingleton-valued and the universe $\mathcal{T}$ arbitrary. By a customary abuse of language, we also sometimes refer to the domain of the projection as the subuniverse. Closure under subsingletons means that $A\,P$ holds for any subsingleton $P:\mathcal{U}$. Closure under sums amounts to saying that if $X:\mathcal{U}$ satisfies $A$ and every $Y\,x$ satisfies $A$ for a family $Y:X\to\mathcal{U}$, then so does $\Sigma\,Y$. Closure under products is defined in the same way with $\Pi$ in place of $\Sigma$.
