Definition 5.1. An $\infty$-category is additive if it is semiadditive and each mapping $\mathbb{E}_{\infty}$-space is grouplike.
Definition 2.1. A Lawvere theory is an $\infty$-category $\mathcal{L}$ which is closed under finite products and generated under finite products by a single distinguished object $1$. An algebra or model of $\mathcal{L}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is a functor $\mathcal{L}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ which preserves finite products.
Definition 3.10. If $\mathcal{V}$ is presentable and closed symmetric monoidal, a $\mathcal{V}$-enriched Lawvere theory is a $\mathcal{V}$-enriched category for which the underlying $\infty$-category is a Lawvere theory.
Definition 28. A minimal model of an operad ${\mathcal{P}}\in\hbox{${\tt Per}$-${\tt Oper}_{1}$}$ is a differential graded (dg) ${\tt Per}$-operad ${\mathfrak{M}}=({\mathfrak{M}},{\partial})$ together with a dg ${\tt Per}$-operad morphism $\rho:{\mathfrak{M}}\to{\mathcal{P}}$ such that (i) the component $\rho(\alpha):({\mathfrak{M}}(\alpha),{\partial})\to({\mathcal{P}}(\alpha),{% \partial}=0)$ of $\rho$ is a homology isomorphism for each $\alpha\in{\tt Per}$, and (ii) the underlying non-dg ${\tt Per}$-operad of ${\mathfrak{M}}$ is free, and the differential ${\partial}$ is quadratic with respect to the natural grading of ${\mathfrak{M}}$.
Definition 40. A degree $s$ linear map $\varpi:{\mathcal{P}}\to{\mathcal{P}}$ of ${\tt Per}$-collections is a degree $s$ derivation of a Markl’s operad ${\mathcal{P}}$ if $\varpi\,\circ_{f}=\circ_{f}(\varpi\otimes 1\!\!1)+\circ_{f}(1\!\!1\otimes% \varpi),$ for every elementary $F\triangleright\alpha\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\to}}\beta$ and the associated operation $\circ_{f}:{\mathcal{P}}(\beta)\otimes{\mathcal{P}}(F)\to{\mathcal{P}}(\alpha)$.
Definition 12. A copermutad is a collection $C\in{\tt Coll}$ together with operations $\delta_{r}:C(\underline{n})\longrightarrow C({r}^{-1}(1))\!\otimes\!C({r}^{-1}% (2)),\ r\in{\tt Surj}(\underline{n},\underline{2}),\ n\geq 2,$ satisfying the obvious dual versions of axioms (6).
Definition 43. A binary quadratic ${\tt Per}$-operad ${\mathcal{P}}$ is Koszul if the canonical map (38) is a component-wise homology isomorphism.
Definition 15. The cobar construction of a copermutad $C$ is the differential graded (dg) permutad ${{\mathbb{\Omega}}}(C):=({\mathbb{P}}(\downarrow\!C),{\partial}_{\mathbb{% \Omega}})$. The dual bar construction of a permutad $A$ satisfying the assumptions of Example 13 is the dg permutad ${\mathbb{D}}(A):={\mathbb{\Omega}}(A^{*})$.
Definition 31. A strongly homotopy permutad is an algebra for the minimal model ${\mathfrak{M}}$ of ${\sf 1}_{{\tt Per}}$.
Definition 5. A permutad is an algebra for the monad ${\mathbb{P}}:{\tt Coll}\to{\tt Coll}$.
Definition 1. A permutad, also called a shuffle algebra, is a monoid for the monoidal product (2).
Definition 14. A degree $s$ derivation of a permutad $A$ is a degree $s$ linear map $\varsigma:A\to A$ of collections such that $\varsigma\,\hbox{\tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{r}=\hbox{\tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{r}(% \varsigma\otimes 1\!\!1)+\hbox{\tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{r}(1\!\!1\otimes\varsigma% ),\ r\in{\tt Surj}(\underline{n},\underline{2}),\ n\geq 2,$ for the structure operations $\hbox{\tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{r}$ in (5). In elements, $\varsigma(a_{1}\hbox{\tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{r}a_{2})=\varsigma(a_{1})\,\hbox{% \tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{r}\,a_{2}+(-1)^{s\cdot\deg(a_{1})}a_{1}\,\hbox{\tiny$% \diamondsuit$}_{r}\,\varsigma(a_{2}),\ a_{i}\in A({r}^{-1}(i)),\ i=1,2.$
Definition 41. The cobar construction of a ${\tt Per}$-cooperad ${\mathcal{C}}$ is the dg ${\tt Per}$-operad ${{\mathbb{\Omega}}}({\mathcal{C}}):=({\mathbb{F}}(\downarrow\!{\overline{% \mathcal{C}}}),{\partial}_{\mathbb{\Omega}})$. The dual bar construction of a ${\tt Per}$-operad ${\mathcal{P}}$ satisfying appropriate finitarity assumptions is the dg ${\tt Per}$-operad ${\mathbb{D}}({\mathcal{P}}):={\mathbb{\Omega}}({\mathcal{P}}^{*})$.
Definition 9. A permutad $A$ is quadratic if it is of the form ${\mathbb{P}}(B)/(S)$, where $(S)$ is the permutadic ideal generated by a subspace $S\subset{\mathbb{P}}^{2}(B)$. Such a quadratic permutad $A$ is binary, if $B(\underline{n})=0$ for $n\not=1$.
Definition 18. A binary quadratic permutad $A$ is Koszul if the canonical map (14) is a component-wise homology isomorphism.
Definition 3. A permutad is a collection $A\in{\tt Coll}$ together with operations $\hbox{\tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{r}:A({r}^{-1}(1))\otimes A({r}^{-1}(2))\to A(% \underline{n})$ defined for each surjection $r\in{\tt Surj}(\underline{n},\underline{2})$. These operations shall satisfy $\hbox{\tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{u}(\hbox{\tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{v}\otimes 1\!\!1)=% \hbox{\tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{t}(1\!\!1\otimes\hbox{\tiny$\diamondsuit$}_{s})$ for each $m\geq 1$ and surjections $u,t:\underline{m}\to\underline{2}$, $s:{t}^{-1}(1)\to\underline{2}$ and $v:{u}^{-1}(2)\to\underline{2}$ such that $t(s\otimes 1\!\!1)=u(1\!\!1\otimes v).$
Definition 36. A ${\tt Per}$-operad ${\mathcal{P}}$ is binary quadratic if it is of the form ${\mathcal{P}}\cong{\mathbb{F}}(E)/(R)$, where (i) the generators $E=\{E(\alpha)\}_{\alpha\in{\tt Per}}$ are such that $E(\alpha)=0$ if $|\alpha|\not=2$, and (ii) the generators $R$ of the ideal of relations form a subcollection of ${\mathbb{F}}^{2}(E)$.
Definition 3.7. For $s\geq 0$, the adelic $s$-cochains may be thought of as functions on $s$-simplices of the poset $\mathfrak{X}$: $C^{s}(\mathfrak{X};A,M)=\prod_{\wp_{0}}A_{\wp_{0}}\prod_{\wp_{1}<\wp_{0},}A_{% \wp_{1}}\prod_{\wp_{2}<\wp_{1}}\cdots\prod_{\wp_{s-1}<\wp_{s-2}}A_{\wp_{s-1}}% \prod_{\wp_{s}<\wp_{s-1}}A_{\wp_{s}}M(\wp_{s}).$
Definition 3.4. (i) An idempotent localization $L:\mathbb{C}\longrightarrow\mathbb{C}$ is an idempotent monad. It consists of the functor $L$, together with a natural transformation $\eta:1\longrightarrow L$ giving a natural equivalence $L\eta=\eta_{L}:L=L\circ 1\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\cong}}{{\longrightarrow}}L\circ L$ (ii) An $\mathfrak{X}$-collection of localizations is a collection $\{L_{\wp}\}$ of localizations for $\wp\in\mathfrak{X}$. An $\mathfrak{X}$-collection is said to be left absorbative if, whenever $\wp_{1}\geq\wp_{2}$, the natural map $A_{\wp_{1}}(\eta_{\wp_{2}}):A_{\wp_{1}}=A_{\wp_{1}}\circ 1\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\cong}}{{\longrightarrow}}A_{\wp_{1}}\circ A_{\wp_{2}}$ is an isomorphism. An $\mathfrak{X}$-collection is right absorbative if, whenever $\wp_{1}\geq\wp_{2}$, the natural map $\eta_{\wp_{1}}:A_{\wp_{2}}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\cong}}{{\longrightarrow}}A_{% \wp_{1}}\circ A_{\wp_{2}}$ is an isomorphism.
Definition 6.1. A monomorphism $m:M\to A$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is said to be subobject-essential if, for a monomorphism $n:N\to A$, one has $M\times_{A}N=0\Rightarrow N=0$. The class of all subobject-essential monomorphisms in $\mathcal{C}$ will be denoted by $\mathrm{Mono}_{SE}(\mathcal{C})$.
Definition 7.1. An object $A$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is said to be $\mathcal{M}$-uniform if a morphism $x\colon X\rightarrow A$ belongs to $\mathcal{M}$ whenever $X\not=0$ and $\mathsf{Ker}(x)=0$.
Definition 5.1. The spectral category $\mathrm{Spec}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{S})$ of $(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{S})$ is the category $\mathcal{C}[(\mathrm{St}(\mathrm{Mono}_{E}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{S})))^{-1}]$ of fractions of $\mathcal{C}$ for the class $\mathrm{St}(\mathrm{Mono}_{E}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{S}))$ of pullback stable $S$-essential mono-morphisms of $\mathcal{C}$. When $\mathcal{S}$ is the class of all monomorphisms in $\mathcal{C}$, we shall simply write $\mathrm{Mono}_{E}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{S})=\mathrm{Mono}_{E}(\mathcal{C})$ and $\mathrm{Spec}(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{S})=\mathrm{Spec}(\mathcal{C})$, and say that $\mathrm{Spec}(\mathcal{C})$ is the spectral category of $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 5.3 (finite presentation). A finite presentation of a category is a pair $(X,R)$ consisting of • a finite quiver $X$, • a finite set $R$ of finite (directed) paths in $X$. The category $\mathopen{\bBigg@{0.8}}\langle X\,|\,R\mathclose{\bBigg@{0.8}}\rangle% \mathclose{}$ presented by such a finite presentation $(X,R)$ is the quotient category of the free category $F_{X}$, freely generated by $X$, modulo the smallest congruence relation on morphisms of $F_{X}$ containing $R$.
Definition 1.2 (residually finite category). A category $C$ is residually finite, if for all morphisms $f$ and $g$ in $C$ with $f\neq g$, there exists a finite category $D$ and a functor $F\colon C\longrightarrow D$ with $F(f)\neq F(g).$
Definition 5.4 (solvability of the word problem). Let $(X,R)$ be a finite presentation of a category. Then the word problem for $(X,R)$ is solvable if the following holds: There exists an algorithm that given as input two finite (directed) paths in $X$ (specified as finite lists of directed edges) decides whether the morphisms in the category $\mathopen{\bBigg@{0.8}}\langle X\,|\,R\mathclose{\bBigg@{0.8}}\rangle% \mathclose{}$ represented by these paths are equal or not.
Definition 4.10 (module categories). Let $R$ be a ring with unit and let $n\in\mathbb{N}$. Then we introduce the following categories: • ${}_{R}\!\operatorname{{\sf FMod}}$: The category of all finitely generated free left $R$-modules and $R$-linear maps. • ${}_{R}\!\operatorname{{\sf FMod}}|_{n}$: The category of all finitely generated free left $R$-modules freely generated by at most $n$ elements and $R$-linear maps.
